But first an intro to Rcpp

Recall the rejection sampler from the Gaussian distribution,

rgaus <- function(n) {
  y <- numeric(n)
  for(i in 1:n) {
    ratio <- 0 
    u <- 1
    while(u > ratio) {
      y0 <- rexp(1) - rexp(1)
      ratio <- exp(- y0^2 / 2 - 0.5 + abs(y0))
      u <- runif(1)
    }
    y[i] <- y0
  }
  y
}

Using cppFunction

library(Rcpp)
cppFunction('NumericVector rgausFast(int n) {
  NumericVector y(n);
  double ratio, u, y0;
  for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    ratio = 0;
    u = 1; 
    while(u > ratio) {
      y0 = rexp(1)[0] - rexp(1)[0];
      ratio = exp(- y0 * y0 / 2 - 0.5 + std::abs(y0));
      u = runif(1)[0];
    }
    y[i] = y0;
  }
  return y;
}'
)

Multivariate distributions

Distributions on \(\mathbb{R}^n\) can be specified by a density. A well known example is the multivariate normal distribution.

How should we simulate from a distribution on \(\mathbb{R}^n\) with density \(f\)?

  • If the coordinates are independent, we can simulate them marginally.

  • For the multivariate normal distribution \(\mathcal{N}(\mu, \Sigma)\) simulation can be done as \(X = C Z + \mu\), with \(Z \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I)\) and \(\Sigma = CC^T\).

  • Rejection and importance sampling can be used, but choosing a good envelope becomes increasingly difficult as \(k\) increases.

Sequential sampling

Suppose that \(X_0 = U_0\) and \[X_k = \alpha X_{k-1} + U_k\] for \(k = 1, \ldots, n\), where \(U_0, \ldots, U_n\) are i.i.d. \(\mathcal{N}(0, 1)\)-distributed.

Then \[X_k = (C U)_k = \alpha^k U_0 + \alpha^{(k-1)} U_1 + \ldots + U_k\] with \(C_{k,l} = \alpha^{k-l}1(k \geq l)\), and \(X = (X_k)_{k=0}^n \sim \mathcal{N}(0, CC^T)\).

It is much faster to use the recursive (sequential) formula than the matrix multiplication for simulation.

Colorado flight

Colorado flight

Let \(X_t \in \mathbb{R}^2\) denote the position at time \(t\), then \[X_t = X_{t-1} + d_t\] with \(d_t\) the velocity.

If we observe \(d_t\) then \[X_t = X_0 + \sum_{s=1}^t d_s.\]

Colorado flight, cumulative errors

If we observe \(\tilde{d}_t = d_t - \epsilon_t\) then \[\tilde{X}_t = X_0 + \sum_{s=1}^t \tilde{d}_s = X_t + \sum_{s = 1}^t \epsilon_s.\]

Our naive prediction of position drifts away by cumulation of errors.

Inertial navigation systems

A combination of measurements from gyroscopes and accelerometers combined with knowledge of initial velocity can be used to compute the velocity at any given later time.

This is in itself a summation (or integration) process, where errors are accumulated.

In this example we suppose for simplicity that velocity is reported by the inertial navigation system as \[\tilde{d}_t = d_t - \epsilon_t\]

Then \[X_t = X_{t-1} + \tilde{d}_t + \epsilon_t.\]

Corrections

Additional measurements \[Y_t = m(X_t) + \delta_t\] with \(\delta_t\) i.i.d. might be used to correct for the cumulation of errors, if the map \(m : \mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathbb{R}\) is informative about the position.

For the Colorado flight, \(m\) is the ground elevation.

How do we incorporate the additional measurements into the summation of the noisy velocities to correct for the errors?

Markov Chains

A sequence \(X_0, X_1, \ldots\) given by update formulas \[X_t = F_t(X_{t-1}, U_t)\] for \(U_t\) i.i.d. and \(F_t\) fixed maps is a Markov chain.

The process on slide 3, \[X_k = \alpha X_{k-1} + U_k,\] is an example of a Markov chain known as the AR(1)-process (autoregressive process with lag 1).

For the AR(1)-process, \(F(x, u) = \alpha x + u.\)

Flight models

We will consider two navigation models of this form.

Model 1: Let \[F_t(x, u) = x + \tilde{d}_t + u\] and \(\epsilon_t = U_t\).

Model 2: Let \[F_t(x, u) = x + \tilde{d}_t + \sigma(x)u\] and \(\epsilon_t = \sigma(X_{t-1})U_t\).

Markov Chains

If the distribution of \(F_t(x, U_t)\) has density \(f_t(\cdot \mid x)\), the density of \(X_0, \ldots, X_t\) is \[ \begin{aligned} f_t(x_{0:t}) & = f_0(x_0) f_1(x_1\mid x_0) \ldots f_t(x_t \mid x_{t-1}) \\ & = f_t(x_{0:(t-1)}) f_t(x_t \mid x_{t-1}), \end{aligned} \] where \(f_0\) is the density of \(X_0\).

We call \(f_t(\cdot \mid x)\) the transition density at time \(t\). If it doesn't depend upon \(t\) we call the Markov chain time homogeneous.

The AR(1)-process is time homogeneous. If also \(U_t \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1)\), the transition density is the Gaussian density with mean \(\alpha x\) and variance \(1\).

Hidden Markov models

Let \(X_0, X_1, \ldots\) be a Markov chain and \[Y_t = G_t(X_t, \delta_t)\] for \(\delta_t\) i.i.d. and \(G_t\) a fixed function.

If the distribution of \(G_t(x, \delta_t)\) has density \(g_t(\cdot \mid x)\), the joint distribution of \((X_0, Y_0), \ldots, (X_t, Y_t)\) has density \[k_t(x_{0:t}, y_{0:t}) = f_t(x_{0:t}) g_t(y_{0:t} \mid x_{0:t})\] where \[g_t(y_{0:t} \mid x_{0:t}) = g_0(y_0 \mid x_0) g_1(y_1 \mid x_1) \ldots g_t(y_t \mid x_t). \]

For navigation, \(G_t(x, \delta) = m(x) + \delta.\)

Navigation

Knowing the noisy velocities and the initial position the HMM allows for a generation of paths and related elevation measurements.

We are interested in reversing this process.

Given the elevation measurements and velocities we are interested in computing the path.

Specifically, we want to compute \[E (X_t \mid Y_0 = y_0, \ldots, Y_t = y_t),\] as a prediction of the position at time \(t\) given the elevation measurements up to time \(t\).

Bayes' Theorem

Bayes' Theorem

\[P(A \mid B) = \frac{P(B \mid A) P(A)}{P(B)}\]

Or for random variables \[ \begin{aligned} P(X \in A \mid Y \in B) & = \frac{P(Y \in B \mid X \in A) P(X \in A)}{P(Y \in B)} \end{aligned} \]

Or for point probabilities \[ \begin{aligned} P(X = x \mid Y = y) & = \frac{P(Y = y \mid X = x) P(X = x)}{P(Y = y)} \end{aligned} \]

Bayes' Theorem

It is a little more tricky for continuous random variables because one-point sets have probability zero.

That \(Y \mid X = x\) has conditional density \(g(y \mid x)\) means by definition that \[ \begin{aligned} P(X \in A, Y \in B) & = \int_A \int_B \underbrace{g(y \mid x) f(x)}_{\textrm{joint dens.}} \ dy dx \end{aligned} \]

Bayes' Theorem

Note that \[g(y \mid x) f(x) = \frac{g(y \mid x) f(x)}{g(y)} g(y).\]

Hence \[P(X \in A, Y \in B) = \int_B \int_A \frac{g(y \mid x) f(x)}{g(y)} g(y) \ dx dy.\]

And by the definition of conditional densities,
\[f(x \mid y) = \frac{g(y \mid x) f(x)}{g(y)}.\]

Hidden Markov Models

The conditional density of \(Y_0, \ldots, Y_t\) given \(X_0 = x_0, \ldots, X_t = x_t\) is
\[g_t(y_{0:t} \mid x_{0:t}).\]

By Bayes' theorem, the conditional density of \(X_0, \ldots, X_t\) given \(Y_0 = y_0, \ldots, Y_t = y_t\) is \[f_t(x_{0:t} \mid y_{0:t}) = \frac{g_t(y_{0:t} \mid x_{0:t}) f_t(x_{0:t})}{g_t(y_{0:t})}.\]

Hidden Markov Models

The numerator, \[g_t(y_{0:t} \mid x_{0:t}) f_t(x_{0:t})\] is directly computable.

The denominator, \[g_t(y_{0:t}) = \int k_t(x_{0:t}, y_{0:t}) \ d x_{0:t},\] is not.

It is the marginal density for \(Y_0, \ldots Y_t\), and it is an unknown normalization constant for the conditional density.

Sequential importance sampling

An importance sampler of \[f_t(x_{0:t} \mid y_{0:t}) \propto g_t(y_{0:t} \mid x_{0:t}) f_t(x_{0:t})\] is obtained by sampling from \(f_t\) (the Markov chain itself).

Then the importance weights will be \[w^{(i)*}_t = g_t(y_{0:t} \mid X^{(i)}_{0:t}) = \prod_{s=0}^t u_s^{(i)}\] where \(u_s^{(i)} = g_s(y_s \mid X^{(i)}_{s})\).

Importance sampling

Since sampling from the Markov chain and computing the weights are carried out sequentially from \(s = 0\) to \(s = t\) this is the sequential importance sampler.

We can compute \[E(X_t \mid Y_0 = 0, \ldots, Y_t = y_t) \simeq \sum_{i=1}^n X_t^{(i)} w^{(i)}_t\] with the standardized weights \[w^{(i)}_t = \frac{w^{(i)*}_t}{\sum_{i=1}^n w^{(i)*}_t}.\]

The \(m\)-function

mfun <- function(x1, x2) {
  x1 <- round((x1 + 5000) / 240.62) + 1
  x2 <- round((x2 + 5000) / 308.37) + 1
  x1 <- pmin(pmax(x1, 1), 160)
  x2 <- pmin(pmax(x2, 1), 125)
  elev[x1 + (x2 - 1) * nrow(elev)]
}

Importance sampling filter

impfilt <- function(y, x0, n, d, qsigma, sigma, sigma0 = 50) {
  t <- length(y)
  d <- array(rep(d, each = n), dim = c(n, t, 2))
  x <- array(0, dim = c(n, t, 2))
  u <- w <- matrix(1 / n, n, t)
  x[, 1, ] <- matrix(rnorm(2 * n, rep(x0, n), sigma0), 
                     n, 2, byrow = TRUE)
  for(s in 2:t) {
    x[, s, ] <- x[, s - 1, ] + d[, s, ] + rnorm(2 * n, 0, qsigma)
    u[, s] <- dnorm(y[s], mfun(x[, s, 1], x[, s, 2]), sigma)
    w[, s] <- u[, s] * w[, s - 1]
    w[, s] <- w[, s] / sum(w[, s])
  }
  list(x = x, u = u, w = w)
}

Weight histograms

The weights have degenerated. Most of them are effectively zero!

Importance sampling and resampling

Weight degeneracy is closely related to the envelope not being optimal.

How can we adaptively get rid of the "bad" proposals of a non-optimal envelope?

The solution is closely related to the ability to approximately sample from \(f_s(\cdot\mid y_{0:s})\) using sampling importance resampling (SIR).

SIR

If \(X^{(1)}, \ldots, X^{(n)}\) are i.i.d. importance samples with standardized weights \(w^{(1)}, \ldots, w^{(n)}\) the measure \[\nu^{(n)} := \sum_{i=1}^n w^{(i)} \delta_{X^{(i)}}\] is an approximation of the target distribution.

We can draw approximate samples from the target by sampling from \(\nu^{(n)}\), which is the same as sampling from \(X^{(1)}, \ldots, X^{(n)}\) with replacement with probabilities \(w^{(1)}, \ldots, w^{(n)}\).

This is the SIR algorithm.

Resampling

To counteract the weight degeneracy in sequential importance sampling we can resample in some or all steps of the algorithm.

The bootstrap filter resamples in every step:

  • Sample \(n\) observations from \(\nu_s^{(n)}.\)
    (This is \(n\) approximate samples from \(f_s(\cdot \mid y_{0:s})\). )
  • Replace \(X^{(1)}_s, \ldots, X^{(n)}_s\) by the resampled observations.
  • Replace the weights by \(1/n\).

Bootstrap filter

bootfilt <- function(y, x0, n, d, qsigma, sigma, sigma0 = 50) {
  t <- length(y)
  d <- array(rep(d, each = n), dim = c(n, t, 2))
  x <- xre <- array(0, dim = c(n, t, 2))
  u <- matrix(1 / n, n, t)
  x[, 1, ] <- matrix(rnorm(2 * n, rep(x0, n), sigma0), 
                     n, 2, byrow = TRUE)
  xre[, 1, ] <- x[, 1, ]
  for(s in 2:t) {
    x[, s, ] <- xre[, s - 1, ] + d[, s, ] + rnorm(2 * n, 0, qsigma)
    u[, s] <- dnorm(y[s], mfun(x[, s, 1], x[, s, 2]), sigma)
    resamp <- sample(n, n, replace = TRUE, prob = u[, s])
    xre[, s, ] <- x[resamp, s, ]   
  }
  list(x = x, u = u)
}
